Prologuc.

The sixplays of Terence are headed by Prologues, in which the poet anticipates criticisms or defends himself against them ; in two of them, the prologues to the Phormio and the Eunuchus, he also retorts by criticising the performances of his critic. It is clear that the Andria was already known to the public, or at least to some portion of it, because Terence states (see ll. 13-16) the ground on which it had been attacked ; but we do not know how this knowledge had been got. The play may have been performed before 166 B. C. ; and the prologue, which we have, may have been written for its second appearance, as was the case with the Hecyra. Yet it seems strange that Terence should make no mention of a previous persormance, if one had really taken place, especially as he distinctly states that the Hecyra had been condemned on the stage, when it was first brought out (sce prologue to that play).
